# Git Workflow Standards

## Branch Naming

- `feat/` - New features
- `fix/` - Bug fixes
- `refactor/` - Code refactoring
- `perf/` - Performance improvements
- `docs/` - Documentation changes
- `test/` - Test additions/changes
- `chore/` - Maintenance tasks

## Commit Message Format (Conventional Commits)

```
type(scope): description

[optional body]

[optional footer]
```

## Types

- `feat`: New feature
- `fix`: Bug fix
- `refactor`: Code refactoring
- `perf`: Performance improvement
- `docs`: Documentation
- `test`: Tests
- `chore`: Maintenance
- `style`: Formatting (no code change)
- `ci`: CI/CD changes

## Examples

```
feat(auth): add password reset functionality
fix(api): resolve null pointer in user service
refactor(utils): extract validation logic
docs(readme): update installation instructions
```

## Commit Message Rules

- Use imperative mood ("add" not "added" or "adds")
- First line < 72 characters
- No emoji or special characters (PowerShell compatibility)
- Include scope when applicable
- Breaking changes: Add `BREAKING CHANGE:` footer

## Git Best Practices

- Commit often, push regularly
- One logical change per commit
- Write clear commit messages
- Review changes before committing
- Use HTTPS for push operations
- Verify repo root before first commit

## Pre-Commit Checklist

- [ ] Code compiles/builds
- [ ] Tests pass
- [ ] Linting passes
- [ ] No secrets committed
- [ ] Commit message follows convention
